{meta
 {:nses [com.blockether.vis.ext.common-meta.core],
  :docs
  {"README.md"
   {:created-at #inst "2026-04-28T08:00:00.000-00:00",
    :abstract
    "Read-only introspection extension for the SCI sandbox. Lets the\nagent inspect its own current turn, conversation history, persisted\nvars, prior attempts, and provider/code failure diagnostics from\ninside `:code`, plus discover the surface and canonical README of\nevery other loaded extension. Returns plain Clojure maps and\nvectors so the model manipulates state structurally instead of\nreaching for raw SQLite. Replaces ad-hoc `sqlite3` triage with the\nbounded `(meta/diagnose)` and `(meta/failures)` calls; replaces\nsymbol-name guessing with `(meta/extensions)` and\n`(meta/extension-readme ...)`.",
    :content
    "\n# Meta extension\n\nPackage: `com.blockether/vis-common-meta`. Source: `extensions/common/vis-common-meta/`.\nCanonical location: inlined under `[meta :docs \"README.md\"]` in\n`META-INF/vis-extension/vis.edn` (shipped in the jar). The LLM reads\nit via `(meta/extension-readme 'meta)` from inside `:code`.\n\nThis opt-in extension lets the agent introspect its own state,\nconversation history, failure diagnostics, and the surface of every\nother loaded extension from inside `:code`. The functions bind under\nthe `meta` alias and return plain Clojure maps or vectors so the agent\ncan manipulate the data structurally.\n\nEvery function is a pure read off the same persistence data the\nprojection layer reads from. Failures return `nil` / `[]`, never throw.\nUse these functions instead of ad-hoc `sqlite3` calls from inside the\nagent when triaging a stalled turn.\n\nAdd the jar to the classpath, or list `com.blockether/vis-common-meta` in\nyour `deps.edn`, to enable it.\n\n## Current turn snapshot\n\nCall: `(meta/turn)`. Snapshot of the current turn as a single map:\n\n```clojure\n{:id          \"uuid\"\n :goal        \"user query text\"\n :status      :running\n :plan        {:goal \"...\" :items [...] :open [...] :decided [...]}\n :breadcrumbs [{:position 0 :breadcrumb \"...\"}]\n :attempts    [{:iteration-id :iteration :code :result :error\n                :stdout :stderr :duration-ms}]\n :errors      [...]\n :failures    [{:source :classification :iteration :message :advice}]\n :iteration   {:current N}\n :cost        {:input-tokens :output-tokens :reasoning-tokens\n               :cached-tokens :total-cost :model}\n :redundancy  {:duplicate-count N :total-count N :fraction 0.0}\n :elapsed-ms  N}\n```\n\nUse this when you want to programmatically manipulate turn-level data.\nFor just reading the plan, breadcrumbs, or iteration pointer, the\nprojection (`<plan>`, `<breadcrumbs>`, `<system_state>`) already\ndelivers them in your prompt.\n\n## Failure list\n\nCall: `(meta/failures)` or `(meta/failures conversation-id)`. Returns\nprovider/schema and code/tool failures as normalized data:\n\n```clojure\n[{:source :provider\n  :classification :provider-schema-rejected\n  :iteration 4\n  :reason :not-a-map\n  :received-type \"String\"\n  :raw-preview \"Looking at what I have so far\"\n  :advice \"...\"}\n {:source :code\n  :classification :regex-unsupported-escape\n  :tool \"vis/rg\"\n  :iteration 9\n  :code \"(vis/rg ...)\"\n  :message \"Unsupported escape character: \\\\|\"\n  :advice \"...\"}]\n```\n\nRecognized classifications include:\n\n- `:provider-schema-rejected` — provider returned prose/string instead\n  of the svar iteration map.\n- `:regex-unsupported-escape` — usually `\\|` in a Clojure string.\n- `:regex-unescaped-quote` — an inner quote split a regex string.\n- `:patch-unbalanced-string` — malformed `vis/patch` EDN payload.\n- `:patch-no-match` — `vis/patch` SEARCH block did not match exactly.\n\nThe one-argument form scans every turn in the given conversation and\nadds `:turn-id` plus `:goal` to each failure.\n\n## Turn diagnosis\n\nCall: `(meta/diagnose)` or `(meta/diagnose conversation-id)`. Returns a\ncompact summary designed as the first stop for stalled-agent triage:\n\n```clojure\n{:turn-id \"uuid\"\n :goal \"...\"\n :status :running\n :failure-count 3\n :by-classification {:provider-schema-rejected 1\n                     :patch-no-match 2}\n :failures [...]\n :next-actions [\"...\"]}\n```\n\nThis is the supported replacement for raw SQLite checks from inside\n`:code`. The function exposes provider previews, parse/tool error\nmessages, classifications, and next actions directly as Clojure data.\n\n## Single conversation snapshot\n\nCall: `(meta/conversation)` or `(meta/conversation conversation-id)`.\nSnapshot of one conversation:\n\n```clojure\n{:id         \"uuid\"\n :channel    :vis\n :title      \"...\"\n :model      \"claude-sonnet-4-5\"\n :created-at #inst \"...\"\n :turns      [{:id :goal :outcome :answer :iterations :total-cost}]\n :turn-count N}\n```\n\nNo-arg form returns the current conversation. Pass a UUID to inspect\nany other conversation in the DB.\n\n## Conversation list\n\nCall: `(meta/conversations)` or `(meta/conversations channel)`. Vector\nof every known conversation, newest-first:\n\n```clojure\n[{:id \"...\" :channel :vis :title \"...\" :created-at #inst \"...\"\n  :turn-count N :external-id \"...\"}]\n```\n\nNo-arg form scans every known channel (`:vis`, `:tui`, `:telegram`,\n`:cli`). Pass a channel keyword to filter.\n\n## Var history\n\nCall: `(meta/var-history sym)` or `(meta/var-history sym conversation-id)`.\nFull version timeline for a var:\n\n```clojure\n[{:value :code :version 0}\n {:value :code :version 1}]\n```\n\nDefaults to the current conversation. Pass a UUID to read from another\nconversation. Accepts a symbol or string for `sym`.\n\n## Search past attempts\n\nCall: `(meta/find-attempts pattern)` or `(meta/find-attempts pattern conversation-id)`.\nRegex search over executed `:code` strings:\n\n```clojure\n[{:turn-id :iteration-id :iteration :code :result :error}]\n```\n\nOne-arg form searches only the current turn's attempts. Two-arg form\nscans every turn of the given conversation. `pattern` accepts either a\nstring, compiled to a `Pattern`, or a `Pattern` directly.\n\n## Extension catalog\n\nCall: `(meta/extensions)`. Vector of every loaded extension, with\nmetadata and a summary descriptor for every doc the extension\ndeclares:\n\n```clojure\n[{:namespace 'com.blockether.vis.ext.common-meta.core\n  :alias     'meta\n  :group     \"meta\"\n  :version   \"0.5.0\"\n  :doc       \"Meta introspection...\"\n  :symbols   [turn conversation conversations var-history\n              find-attempts failures diagnose\n              extensions extension-docs extension-doc\n              extension-readme]\n  :docs      [{:name       \"README.md\"\n               :created-at #inst \"2026-04-28\"\n               :abstract   \"Read-only introspection extension...\"\n               :links      [{:to-id 'vis :to-doc \"README.md\"\n                             :context \"Companion filesystem extension\"}\n                            {:url     \"https://arxiv.org/abs/2512.24601\"\n                             :context \"RLM paper\"}\n                            {:file    \"packages/vis-runtime/.../extension.clj\"\n                             :context \"Loader implementation\"}]\n               :reflinks   [{:from-id 'vis :from-doc \"README.md\"\n                             :context \"...\"}]}]}\n ...]\n```\n\nUse it as the first stop when you need to discover what surfaces are\navailable before reaching for a specific tool. Summaries omit the\nMarkdown body so the catalog stays small — pull the full descriptor\n(including `:content`) with `(meta/extension-doc ...)` only when\nneeded.\n\n## Extension docs catalog\n\nCall: `(meta/extension-docs)` or `(meta/extension-docs ext-ref)`. The\nno-arg form returns a map keyed by extension id symbol; the one-arg\nform returns the summary list for a single extension. Each entry\ncarries the structured fields except `:content`:\n\n```clojure\n(meta/extension-docs 'meta)\n;; => [{:name       \"README.md\"\n;;      :created-at #inst \"2026-04-28\"\n;;      :abstract   \"Read-only introspection extension...\"\n;;      :links      [...]   ;; outgoing references authored in vis.edn\n;;      :reflinks   [...]}  ;; inbound references derived by the loader\n;;     ...]\n```\n\nUse this as the index: scan abstracts and `:links` to decide which\nfull doc is worth pulling with `(meta/extension-doc ...)`.\n\n## Extension doc body\n\nCall: `(meta/extension-doc ext-ref doc-name)`. Returns the full\ndescriptor map for one declared doc, inlined in the extension's\n`META-INF/vis-extension/vis.edn` manifest under\n`[<id> :docs <doc-name>]`:\n\n```clojure\n(meta/extension-doc 'meta \"README.md\")\n;; => {:name       \"README.md\"\n;;     :created-at #inst \"2026-04-28\"\n;;     :abstract   \"Read-only introspection extension...\"\n;;     :content    \"# Meta extension\\n...\"   ;; full Markdown body\n;;     :links      [...]\n;;     :reflinks   [...]}\n```\n\n`ext-ref` may be:\n\n- the id symbol (`'meta`),\n- the id as a keyword or string (`:meta`, `\"meta\"`),\n- the alias-ns symbol (`'vis.ext.meta`),\n- the full extension namespace symbol (`'com.blockether.vis.ext.common-meta.core`).\n\nReturns `nil` when the extension is not registered or ships no doc by\nthat name.\n\n## Link types\n\n`:links` are author-declared in `vis.edn`. The loader recognizes four\nshapes:\n\n- Cross-extension doc:\n  `{:to-id <id> :to-doc <doc-name> :context \"...\"}`\n- Same-extension doc (omit `:to-id`):\n  `{:to-doc <doc-name> :context \"...\"}`\n- External URL:\n  `{:url \"https://...\" :context \"...\"}`\n- Repo file:\n  `{:file \"path/to/file.clj\" :context \"...\"}`\n\n`:reflinks` are computed automatically by inverting every cross-ext\nand same-ext link in the registry. URL and file links produce no\nreflinks. Authors who write `:reflinks` by hand are violating the\ncontract; the loader overwrites them on every merge.\n\n## Extension README\n\nCall: `(meta/extension-readme ext-ref)`. Convenience wrapper for\n`(meta/extension-doc ext-ref \"README.md\")`. Every extension is\nrequired to ship a README, so this always works for a registered\nextension.\n\n```clojure\n(meta/extension-readme 'meta)\n(meta/extension-readme 'com.blockether.vis.ext.common-meta.core)\n(meta/extension-readme :vis)             ;; vis-common-editing\n(println (meta/extension-readme 'meta))  ;; pretty-print full doc\n```\n\n## When to use it\n\n- You need failure triage without leaving the sandbox:\n  `(meta/diagnose)` or `(meta/failures)`.\n- You need to verify what an extension actually does:\n  `(meta/extension-readme 'some-ext)` instead of guessing from symbol\n  names.\n- You need to programmatically manipulate state:\n  `(filter :error (:attempts (meta/turn)))`.\n- You want to inspect a different conversation than the one you're\n  currently in.\n- You want regex search over historical attempts.\n- You want token / cost visibility.\n\n## When not to use it\n\n- For state already in the projection: `<plan>`, `<breadcrumbs>`,\n  `<system_state>`, `<var_index>`. Reading the projection is free;\n  calling `meta/*` costs an iteration round-trip via `:code`.\n- As a substitute for setting `:doc` on code blocks. The right way to\n  carry purpose into `<var_index>` is the spec field, not a runtime\n  introspection call.\n- For schema or migration debugging outside the agent. Host-side\n  post-mortems can still inspect SQLite directly when needed.\n\n## Implementation notes\n\n- **Environment-aware via `:before-fn` injection.** Each implementation\n  function takes the environment map as its first parameter. The shared\n  `inject-environment` hook prepends that map to the args vector, so\n  the model still calls `(meta/turn)` with zero arguments.\n- **No side effects, never throws.** Every function is a pure read.\n  Misconfigured DB or missing context returns `nil` / `[]`; the\n  agent's iteration is unaffected.\n- **No schema change.** The extension reads existing conversation,\n  query, iteration, and expression rows through the persistence facade.\n- **README discovery.** Every extension is expected to declare its\n  canonical README inline in `META-INF/vis-extension/vis.edn` under\n  `[<id> :docs \"README.md\"]` (see `AGENTS.md` ▸ \"Every extension\n  declares itself in vis.edn with an inline README\"). Each declared\n  doc descriptor MUST carry `:abstract` and `:content` as plain\n  strings — the abstract is its own EDN field, NOT a YAML\n  frontmatter block parsed out of Markdown. `(meta/extensions)`,\n  `(meta/extension-docs ...)`, `(meta/extension-doc ...)`, and\n  `(meta/extension-readme ...)` all read directly from this\n  structured registry.\n",
    :links
    [{:to-id vis,
      :to-doc "README.md",
      :context "Companion filesystem and code-editing toolbelt"}
